specJson.name: brightics.function.timeseries$auto_arima_predict
specJson.label: Auto ARIMA Predict
specJson.description:
Auto ARIMA model automatically discovers the optimal parameters for an ARIMA model, settling on a single fitted ARIMA model.

Auto ARIMA works by conducting differencing tests (i.e., Kwiatkowski–Phillips–Schmidt–Shin, Augmented Dickey-Fuller or Phillips–Perron) to determine the order of differencing, `d`, and then fitting models within ranges of defined `Max p`, `Max_q` ranges. 

ARIMA is usually used to monitor if there is abnormal value on trend by reviewing data on a weekly/monthly basis or to predict future values on a quarter/yearly basis. A strength of ARIMA compared to ARMA is it can be adapted to data which shows non-stationary series. Stationary series is a type of series which average and variance are unchangeable regardless of time transition. In case of non-stationary series, it is normally analyzed after stabilizing it with log or difference.
specJson.summary: This function predicts a time series data using a non-seasonal Auto ARIMA model.

md: # Auto ARIMA Predict This function predicts a time series data using a non-seasonal Auto ARIMA model. ## Description Auto ARIMA model automatically discovers the optimal parameters for an ARIMA model, settling on a single fitted ARIMA model. Auto ARIMA works by conducting differencing tests (i.e., Kwiatkowski–Phillips–Schmidt–Shin, Augmented Dickey-Fuller or Phillips–Perron) to determine the order of differencing, `d`, and then fitting models within ranges of defined `Max p`, `Max_q` ranges. ARIMA is usually used to monitor if there is abnormal value on trend by reviewing data on a weekly/monthly basis or to predict future values on a quarter/yearly basis. A strength of ARIMA compared to ARMA is it can be adapted to data which shows non-stationary series. Stationary series is a type of series which average and variance are unchangeable regardless of time transition. In case of non-stationary series, it is normally analyzed after stabilizing it with log or difference. Reference - - ## Properties ### VA #### INPUT 1. **model***: (Model) Trained Auto ARIMA Time Series model. #### OUTPUT 1. **table**: (Table) A table that contains prediction column which has the same name with `Input Columns`. #### PARAMETER 1. **Prediction Number***: Number of rows to predict. ### Python #### USAGE ``` auto_arima_predict(model, prediction_num) ``` #### INPUT 1. **model***: (Model) Trained Auto ARIMA Time Series model. #### OUTPUT 1. **table**: (Table) A table that contains prediction column which has the same name with `input_cols`. #### PARAMETER 1. **prediction_num***: Number of rows to predict. * Type: *int* * Default / Range: (value >= 1) ## Example ### VA **[Related Tutorial]** **[Sample Model]** In this tutorial workflow, sample_timeseries data is used to train an Auto ARIMA model. The generated model is afterward applied to predict the _future value at certain time point_ by using an Auto ARIMA Predict function. The parameter settings used in the function are shown below. ++Parameters++ 1. **Prediction Number***: 3 ### Python ``` from brightics.function.timeseries import auto_arima_predict input_model = models[0] result = auto_arima_predict(model=input_model, prediction_num=3) output = result['table'] ``` In this python script, sample_timeseries data is used to train an Auto ARIMA model. The generated model is afterward applied to predict the _future value at certain time point_ by using an Auto ARIMA Predict function.
